        "videoSolution": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KLlXCFG5TkE",
        "textSolution": "## ✅ HashMap Approach (Optimal)\n\n### Java Code\n\n`java\nimport java.util.HashMap;\n\nclass Solution {\n    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {\n        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {\n            int complement = target - nums[i];\n\n            if (map.containsKey(complement)) {\n                return new int[]{ map.get(complement), i };\n            }\n\n            map.put(nums[i], i);\n        }\n\n        return new int[]{-1, -1};\n    }\n}\n`\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation\n\n### 1️⃣ Create HashMap\n\n- Key → number from array\n- Value → index of that number\n- Enables O(1) lookup for the required pair\n\n### 2️⃣ Traverse Array\n\n- Loop through each element once\n- Time complexity becomes O(n)\n\n### 3️⃣ Find Complement\n\n- Compute: `target - nums[i]`\n- If it exists in map, we found the pair\n\n### 4️⃣ Check Before Storing\n\n- If complement is already in map, return indices\n- Prevents using the same element twice\n\n### 5️⃣ Store Current Element\n\n- Add current number and index to map after checking\n\n### 6️⃣ Fallback Return\n\n- Returns `{-1, -1}` for compiler safety\n\n---\n\n## ⏱️ Complexity\n\n- Time: O(n)\n- Space: O(n)\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 Interview One-Liner\n\n'I iterate once, compute the complement, check if it exists in a HashMap, and return indices immediately. This reduces time complexity from O(n²) to O(n).'\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Memory Trick\n\n**Check first, store later**"
